    <section class="hol-hero">
      <p class="hol-series">&#8213; Unmasking the Holidays · December &#8213;</p>
      <h1 class="hol-title">Christmas</h1>
      <p class="hol-sub">30 Traditions. The sun god's birthday. The tree Jeremiah described.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="hol-section">
      <div class="hol-prose">
        <p>Christmas (December 25th) replaced the Roman festival of Saturnalia and the birthday of Sol Invictus — the "Unconquered Sun." December 25th is the winter solstice in the ancient Roman calendar, the day the sun's strength begins to return. The "rebirth of the sun" was celebrated across the ancient world: in Egypt as the birthday of Horus, in Babylon as the birthday of Tammuz, in Rome as the birthday of Sol Invictus. It was never celebrated as the birthday of Yahushua in the first three centuries of the assembly.</p>
        <p>The Christmas tree connects directly to the Asherah poles Yahuah commanded His people to cut down and burn. Jeremiah 10:1–5 describes the practice almost word for word: "For the customs of the peoples are futile: for one cuts a tree from the forest... They decorate it with silver and gold; they fasten it with nails and hammers so that it will not topple." The Yule log was burned to coax the sun back. Santa Claus is a syncretic figure blending St. Nicholas with Norse and pagan winter mythology.</p>
        <p>This study examines 30 Christmas traditions — from the December 25th date to the ornaments, the Yule log, Santa Claus, and the Christmas ham — tracing each one to Saturnalia, Yule, and the ancient worship practices Yahuah explicitly condemned.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
